WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.160
Americans have long been the biggest consumers on&nbsp;
the planet – and American consumption has grown&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:06.160 --> 00:00:13.360
and grown over time. Americans bought sixty-eight&nbsp;
new items of clothing last year – a huge increase&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:13.360 --> 00:00:19.120
from the twelve items a year that they used&nbsp;
to buy in the 1980’s. Their spending on that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:19.120 --> 00:00:26.560
clothing however, has fallen. In the 1980’s the&nbsp;
average American spent 7% of their annual income&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:26.560 --> 00:00:34.000
on clothing - while today they just spend just 3%.&nbsp;
So, for less than half the spending shoppers today&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:40.160
are getting almost six times as many items.
According to JP Morgan - since the turn of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:40.160 --> 00:00:46.720
century, real personal consumption growth in&nbsp;
the United States (meaning inflation adjusted&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:46.720 --> 00:00:52.880
consumption growth) averaged two and a half&nbsp;
percent - but in the second half of 2023,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:52.880 --> 00:01:00.400
that rose above 3% even with the higher interest&nbsp;
rates and elevated, but declining, inflation.
&nbsp;

00:01:00.400 --> 00:01:07.440
Consumer spending accounts for almost 70% of US&nbsp;
GDP and while consumption in Europe has grown&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:07.440 --> 00:01:13.920
over time too, Europeans tend to spend less&nbsp;
time at work than Americans, do more work at&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:13.920 --> 00:01:21.200
home and they have lower overall consumption.
For decades, the American consumer has powered&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:21.200 --> 00:01:27.240
not just the world's biggest economy but the&nbsp;
entire global economy. According to the World Bank&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:27.240 --> 00:01:35.120
– Americans make up around one third of global&nbsp;
consumer spending but are only 4% of the global&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:35.120 --> 00:01:42.080
population. We should only be so surprised by&nbsp;
this – Americans are amongst the most productive&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:42.080 --> 00:01:48.400
workers in the world and thus are amongst the&nbsp;
best paid – the fact that they are both busy and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:48.400 --> 00:01:55.920
highly paid makes them naturally big consumers.
Over the last fifty years, the United States has&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:55.920 --> 00:02:01.360
had just four significant dips in consumer&nbsp;
spending – the biggest having occurred in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:01.360 --> 00:02:07.840
2020 when the global pandemic struck. At the&nbsp;
start of the pandemic Americans slashed all&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:07.840 --> 00:02:14.000
spending and we saw a massive boost in personal&nbsp;
savings as the government pumped a load of money&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:20.480
into the economy. Nobody was traveling. People&nbsp;
couldn’t eat out. They didn’t lose their jobs&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:20.480 --> 00:02:26.800
and could suddenly work from home. Most Americans&nbsp;
continued to earn money and were simply spending&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:26.800 --> 00:02:32.800
less. Poorer Americans who lived paycheck&nbsp;
to paycheck suddenly had free time for the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:32.800 --> 00:02:38.400
first time in their working lives – and due&nbsp;
to stimulus checks also had savings – which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:38.400 --> 00:02:45.040
many had never really had before. People's bank&nbsp;
accounts grew. And once the covid restrictions&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:45.040 --> 00:02:51.760
started to ease, they went on a spending spree. 
While Americans stopped spending on restaurants,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:51.760 --> 00:02:57.440
vacations and their daily commutes during the&nbsp;
pandemic, they spent much more on physical&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:57.440 --> 00:03:03.520
goods – they cancelled gym memberships and bought&nbsp;
things like treadmills. During that period – the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:03.520 --> 00:03:11.520
world spent 5% more on physical goods but the&nbsp;
undefeated American consumer spent 10% more.
&nbsp;

00:03:11.520 --> 00:03:17.600
I asked my viewers in a community post - what&nbsp;
goods Americans buy that the rest of the world&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:17.600 --> 00:03:23.440
doesn’t – the most popular answer was guns&nbsp;
and ammo – there were also huge trucks – and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:23.440 --> 00:03:29.280
of course truck nuts. Whenever I see things&nbsp;
like that, I always imagine how confused the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:29.280 --> 00:03:34.720
Chinese factory workers who make them must be.&nbsp;
I imagine they have long conversations in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:34.720 --> 00:03:39.280
evening with their friends and families&nbsp;
about who buys these things and why.
&nbsp;

00:03:40.640 --> 00:03:46.960
There is no way around it though, Americans do&nbsp;
love spending and not just on necessities like&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:46.960 --> 00:03:53.280
tattoos, baseball caps, massive water bottles&nbsp;
and aerosol cheese. I spoke to a friend a few&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:53.280 --> 00:03:59.760
