00:09:25.040 --> 00:09:31.840
The way the clothing industry works has changed a&nbsp;
lot over the years. In the 1980’s it used to take&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:31.840 --> 00:09:37.920
around nine months for an item of clothing to be&nbsp;
designed – a big store like Sears would then order&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:37.920 --> 00:09:44.240
each item in bulk in a variety of different sizes&nbsp;
– and these items would be available in the store&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:44.240 --> 00:09:50.960
for maybe six months. If they didn’t sell this was&nbsp;
a problem – and for this reason a lot of thought,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:50.960 --> 00:09:56.400
went into finding the right items and&nbsp;
providing quality at every price point.
&nbsp;

00:09:56.400 --> 00:10:03.680
The term fast fashion first appeared in 1989 in&nbsp;
a New York Times article about a new retailer&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:03.680 --> 00:10:11.040
at the time called Zara. Zara they explained was&nbsp;
able to go from idea – to having an item in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:11.040 --> 00:10:18.160
store in 15 days because they had built a network&nbsp;
of factories around their headquarters in Spain.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:18.160 --> 00:10:24.000
They would manufacture small test batches of&nbsp;
clothes - ship them to the stores – discontinue&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:30.320
the ones that didn’t sell and ramp production in&nbsp;
the items that customers bought. Their approach&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:30.320 --> 00:10:36.320
didn’t require them to predict trends – they&nbsp;
just had to respond quickly to demand. They&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:36.320 --> 00:10:41.680
were able to make copies of high-end designer&nbsp;
clothes within weeks – and make them available&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:41.680 --> 00:10:49.280
cheaply by using low quality fabrics and zips.
Fast fashion brands over time started putting&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:49.280 --> 00:10:54.240
spandex in everything – as the more the&nbsp;
fabric stretches – the fewer sizes you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:54.240 --> 00:10:59.760
have to make – this reduces manufacturing&nbsp;
costs even further – but it also means that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:59.760 --> 00:11:05.920
clothes never fit all that well to begin&nbsp;
with and they wear out very quickly.
&nbsp;

00:11:05.920 --> 00:11:11.040
The same sort of thing that happened with&nbsp;
clothing happened with furniture too. People&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:11.040 --> 00:11:17.360
were happy to buy disposable furniture as long&nbsp;
as it was cheap and on trend. We started to see&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:17.360 --> 00:11:23.200
manufactured goods where plastic was used where&nbsp;
metal used to go and glue was used instead of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:23.200 --> 00:11:30.400
fasteners. These new products were cheap – which&nbsp;
people like – but they didn’t really last.
&nbsp;

00:11:30.960 --> 00:11:38.000
Chinese brands like Shein and Temu managed to&nbsp;
undercut Zara – by moving even faster - having&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:43.680
no physical stores – not owning the factories&nbsp;
(instead treating them like uber drivers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:43.680 --> 00:11:50.480
hooked up to an app) and exploiting a tax&nbsp;
loophole known as the de minimis exemption.
&nbsp;

00:11:50.480 --> 00:11:58.000
The de minimis exemption became law in the United&nbsp;
States in 1930, to allow Americans to skip import&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:03.600
duties for small-value shipments. It was put&nbsp;
in place so that people could bring souvenirs&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:03.600 --> 00:12:09.760
home from their holidays without being taxed. Most&nbsp;
countries around the world have a version of this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:09.760 --> 00:12:15.920
rule – but the United States had the highest&nbsp;
exemption rate of $800 dollars per item. 
&nbsp;

00:12:15.920 --> 00:12:21.120
Americans who have ordered goods from&nbsp;
another country online that cost less than&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:21.120 --> 00:12:26.720
$800 dollars over the last ten years have&nbsp;
benefited from the de minimis exemption.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:26.720 --> 00:12:33.040
If they had bought the same item from a local&nbsp;
store, the price would have been a lot higher&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:33.040 --> 00:12:38.160
as it would have had to include the cost&nbsp;
of manufacturing, shipping, warehousing,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:38.160 --> 00:12:43.600
along with the store’s rent, and the wages&nbsp;
of the U.S. employee who works there. 
&nbsp;

00:12:43.600 --> 00:12:50.160
Both Republicans and Democrats have talked about&nbsp;
ending this exemption for quite some time – as it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:50.160 --> 00:12:55.520
made it impossible for stores to compete with&nbsp;
brands like Temu and Shein – who could avoid&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:55.520 --> 00:13:02.800
most of those costs and pay none of the taxes or&nbsp;
fees a larger-volume importer would have to pay.
&nbsp;

00:13:02.800 --> 00:13:09.360
The de minimis loophole hasn’t yet closed — but&nbsp;
it’s about to. Starting on May 2nd, packages&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:09.360 --> 00:13:17.600
from China will be hit with a 120 percent tax on&nbsp;
the value of the goods or a $100 flat fee, which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:17.600 --> 00:13:24.160
will increase to $200 per package this June.
With the dollar almost ten percent off its&nbsp;&nbsp;

